---
title: "Linear Universal Approximation Theorem"
date: "2026-03-03"
description: "A linear map can approximate any function if you encode and decode in high enough dimensions"
tags: ["machine-learning", "approximation-theory", "linear-algebra"]
---

The Linear Universal Approximation Theorem is a theorem I made up that says you can represent any function as a linear function as long as you map the inputs and outputs to an arbitrarily high dimension space with an appropriate nonlinear transformation.
Unlike the standard Universal Approximation Theorem that says how certain sufficiently large neural networks with nonlinear activation functions can approximate any function to an arbitrary degree of accuracy, the Linear Universal Approximation Theorem places its analogous nonlinearities only when encoding inputs and decoding outputs.
I don't know if this idea has been formally expressed anywhere, but it's related to ideas like the kernel trick with Support Vector Machines that makes data linearly separable in a higher dimensional space.
There's a lot of value in making the core of neural networks linear, such as being able to represent it with a single matrix multiplication, and the fact that the loss function can be made convex with respect to certain parameters.

Let's start off with demonstrating a proof in the discrete inputs and outputs case.
* show function with discrete inputs and outputs

This can also be extended to continuous inputs and outputs.
* show simple linear interpolation between predefined input and output encodings

---

* show motivating example on the topic of generalization where f(0) = 1, f(1) = 2, f(2) = 0, f(3) = 4, f(4) = 5, f(5) = 3 and how this can be done with 4x4 matrix

* lead into the almost orthogonal vectors blog post idea where you can compress things with almost orthogonal vectors and linear map between them

* implications: LLMs can work even if all layers are fully linear (e.g. no activation function in MLP needed), and this makes a lot of sense to do when they're primarily known to have linear features in the residual stream, easier to train a convex function with no vanishing gradients or getting trapped by local minima
* note: in practice, inputs and outputs should be constrained to a hypersphere so you can do dot product cosine similarity, and numerical inputs can be turned into angles when transforming them into inputs kinda like RoPE embeddings
